properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 3:25PM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
Rainfall of around 6 inches has fallen around Yakutat, and rivers
and streams continue to rise as of mid-afternoon. Rainfall looks
to end soon as it pushes to the west of the area. This will allow
rivers and streams to crest and begin to fall. At this time, other
than high water around the area, there have been no impacts with
this system.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 3:25PM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
As a ridge continues to build over Southeast Alaska and sunny
weather expands in coverage Tuesday, we are expecting more
temperatures around or above 60 degrees. Some temperatures could
approach 70 degrees. But the warming could be localized as any
channel breezes developing could lower high temperatures from
expectations, given chilly sea surface temperatures. Even as
clouds move in Wednesday, it could be nearly as warm as Tuesday.

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 7:04PM EDT by NWS Binghamton NY
properties.description:
At 658 PM EDT, a line of heavy snow showers was located from near
Otselic to East Freetown. Movement was east at 25 mph. Between 7 PM
and 8 PM, the snow showers will affect Norwich, Pharsalia, Plymouth,
Oxford, Sherburne, Cincinnatus, Preston, New Berlin and Columbus.

Expect visibilities to briefly fall below a half mile in the snow
showers. Slow down and allow extra time to reach your destination.

NWSheadline: HEAVY SNOW SHOWERS WILL AFFECT EASTERN CORTLAND AND NORTHERN CHENANGO COUNTIES

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 7:00PM EDT by NWS Albany NY
properties.description:
At 658 PM EDT, an line of heavy snow showers was located along a
line extending from near Central Bridge to near Cobleskill to near
Richmondville to Breakabeen to Stamford. Movement was east at 25 mph.

Winds in excess of 30 mph are possible with this line of heavy snow
showers.

This line of heavy snow showers will be near...
Breakabeen around 705 PM EDT.
Schoharie and Central Bridge around 710 PM EDT.
North Blenheim around 715 PM EDT.
Middleburgh, Gilboa, Prattsville and Livingstonville around 720 PM
EDT.

Other locations impacted by this line of heavy snow showers include
West Settlement, Huntersland, Warnerville, Carlisle, Broome Center,
Becker Corners, West Fulton, Shutts Corners, Barnerville and
Eminence.

This includes Interstate 88 between exits 20 and 23.

Visibilities will drop quickly to less than a half of a mile in this
area of heavy snow.

Icy roads are possible as the snow melts on the roads then quickly
refreezes.

Conditions can deteriorate rapidly in winter weather situations. Be
prepared for snow or ice covered roads. Slow down and allow extra
time when traveling.

NWSheadline: AN LINE OF HEAVY SNOW SHOWERS WILL AFFECT WEST CENTRAL GREENE AND SCHOHARIE COUNTIES

properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 4:00PM PDT by NWS Reno NV
properties.description:
Active weather pattern returns Tuesday night as low pressure moves
into the region. This is a much weaker storm than others we have
seen this season. Even though some light to moderate rainfall is
expected with this storm, no flooding is expected at this time.

Snow levels will start out near 8000 feet Tuesday evening, then
fall to near 6000 feet by Wednesday morning. Snow amounts in the
High Sierra above 7000 feet will be around 4 to 8 inches by noon
on Wednesday, with up to a couple inches down to 6000 feet
including Lake Tahoe. Most precipitation below 6000 feet will be
rain.

Showers continue Wednesday afternoon and Thursday morning with an
additional inch or two of snow above 6000 feet by Thursday
morning. Plan on widespread snow pellet showers across the region
on Wednesday afternoon along with a chance of thunder as well.

Anyone with travel plans over the Sierra passes Wednesday morning
or Thursday morning should be prepared for the potential for slow
downs and chain controls. Road conditions during the daylight
hours on Wednesday will likely improve drastically.

NWSheadline: UNSETTLED WEATHER RETURNS TO EASTERN CALIFORNIA AND WESTERN NEVADA THIS WEEK

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued March 18 at 4:59PM MDT expiring March 22 at 5:00PM MDT by NWS Rapid City SD
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Rapid City has issued a

* Flood Advisory for...
Snowmelt and ice jam in...
Northeastern Campbell County in northeastern Wyoming...

* Until 500 PM MDT Friday.

* At 458 PM MDT, gauge reports and trained spotters indicated low
land flooding along the Little Powder River near Weston. Ongoing
snowmelt and ice jams will continue to produce low land flooding
through the week, or until all of the ice is out of the river and
most of the snow has melted.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Areas along the Little Powder River around Weston to the Wyoming
and Montana state line.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

properties.headline: Small Craft Advisory issued March 18 at 6:59PM EDT expiring March 20 at 7:00AM EDT by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
properties.description:
Gusty north to northeast winds will develop behind a cold front
this evening, with seas building to 4 to 6 feet late tonight and
early Tuesday morning. Expect winds to increase to 25 to 35 knots
later Tuesday into Tuesday night between high pressure to the
north and low pressure developing to the south. Seas will build to
6 to 11 feet late Tuesday and Tuesday night, highest central and
southern waters.
* WINDS...Northeast 15 to 25 kt with gusts up to 30 kt. A few
brief gusts to around 35 kts are possible early this evening.

* SEAS...4 to 6 feet.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 25 to 33 knots
and/or seas of 6 feet or greater are expected to produce
hazardous wave conditions to small craft. Inexperienced mariners,
especially those operating smaller vessels should avoid
navigating in these conditions.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 5:27PM CDT expiring March 20 at 9:00AM CDT by NWS North Platte NE
properties.description:
Elkhorn River near Ewing affecting Holt County.

.Flooding will continue along the Elkhorn River in Holt county
from Ewing, upstream to O'Neill, Atkinson and Stuart. High flows
will continue for the next several days as warmer temperatures
contribute to runoff from ice and snow melt.
The Flood Warning continues for
The Elkhorn River near Ewing.
* until Wednesday morning.
* At 4:45 PM Monday the stage was 9.4 feet.
* Flood stage is 9.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is occuring and forecast to continue.
* Forecast...The river will hold nearly steady around 9.5 feet
this evening. The river level is expected to start slowly falling
late tonight. The river should drop below the flood stage of 9.0
feet late Tuesday morning, and then continue falling after that.
* Impact...At 9.5 feet...Minor flooding should be anticipated along
and near the Elkhorn River. Residents of Ewing should take
precautions to protect property and livestock.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Do not drive your vehicle into areas where water covers the roadway.
The water depth may be too great to allow your car to cross safely
and the road beneath may not be intact. Vehicles caught in rising
waters should be abandoned quickly.

Do not let children play near the river during high water.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 6:14PM EDT expiring March 23 at 9:00AM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
properties.description:
Wabash River...White River...


.Flooding continued late Monday afternoon in western Indiana along
much of the Wabash River from around Covington southward, and in
southwestern Indiana on the White River at Petersburg and Hazleton.
The flood crest on the Wabash was in the vicinity of Hutsonville and
Riverton.  The crest on the White River was slightly past Hazleton.
Flooding is expected to end by Saturday evening, March 23rd.

This flooding is a result of heavy rain from March 9th that was
supplemented by additional rainfall on March 14th.  The latter rain
event totaled up to two plus inches in southwest Indiana.

The only precipitation expected this week will come Tuesday night
and Wednesday with rain amounts less than two tenths of an inch.
This will allow rivers to return to close to normal levels.

Flooding is mainly expected to affect agricultural land and
bottomlands.  Some river cabins may be affected from Terre Haute to
Riverton on the Wabash River.
The Flood Warning continues for
The Wabash River at Riverton.
* until Saturday morning.
* At  5:00 PM Monday the stage was 17.7 feet.
* Flood stage is 15.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is occurring and Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...It will rise to near 17.7 feet by this evening then
begin falling. It will fall below flood stage Friday evening.
* At 18.0 feet...Extensive lowland flooding is in progress.  High
water surrounds many river cabins.  Access to most river cabins is
by boat only.  Levees begin to protect farmland.  Extensive
flooding of Leaverton Park occurs in Palestine, Illinois.
properties.instruction:
Precautionary/Preparedness Actions...

Motorists should never drive into flood water. Turn around and go
another way. Keep children away from flooded areas. Recreational and
agricultural interests should remain alert to changing river
conditions.

For detailed flood information go to weather.gov/ind on the web and
click on rivers and lakes.

properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued March 18 at 2:55PM PDT expiring March 19 at 5:00PM PDT by NWS Medford OR
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Medford has issued a Beach
Hazards Statement for an enhanced risk of sneaker waves...which
is in effect from 11 PM PDT this evening through Tuesday
afternoon.

* Hazards...Elevated risk of sneaker waves.

* Timing...Monday evening through Tuesday afternoon.

* Locations Include...Along the south Oregon coast from Florence
to the California state line, especially for west and
northwest facing beaches.

* Potential Impacts...Sudden and unusually high beach run-up is
possible. This can take beachgoers by surprise resulting in
possible injury or drowning. Logs and other debris can become
lifted and floated, increasing risk to those in or near the
water.

* View the hazard area in detail at
https://www.wrh.noaa.gov/mfr/HAZARD
properties.instruction:
A Beach Hazards Statement is issued when threats such as rip
currents...longshore currents...sneaker waves and other hazards
create life-threatening conditions in the surf zone. Caution
should be used when in or near the water.

NWSheadline: BEACH HAZARDS STATEMENT IN EFFECT FROM 11 PM PDT THIS EVENING THROUGH TUESDAY AFTERNOON

properties.areaDesc: Northern Monterey Bay; San Francisco Peninsula Coast; Coastal North Bay Including Point Reyes National Seashore; Southern Monterey Bay and Big Sur Coast; San Francisco
properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued March 18 at 2:32PM PDT expiring March 19 at 11:00PM PDT by NWS San Francisco CA
properties.description:
..INCREASED RISK OF SNEAKER WAVES TUESDAY..

.A long period westerly swell will arrive early Tuesday morning
and bring an increase risk of sneaker waves throughout the day and
into the evening. Expect long lulls between largest sets.
Beachgoers should use caution along area beaches. The risk of
sneaker waves will decrease as the period decreases Tuesday night.
The National Weather Service in San Francisco has issued a Beach
Hazards Statement for increased risk of sneaker waves, which is
in effect from late tonight through Tuesday evening.

* HAZARDS...Increased risk of sneaker waves on northern and
central California beaches.

* TIMING...Tuesday 4 AM to 11 PM.

* LOCATION...Coastline from Sonoma County south through Monterey
County. In particular west facing beaches...including but not
limited to...Ocean beach...Montara State Beach...Halfmoon Bay
State Beach...Manresa State Beach...Monastery Beach and Marina
State Beach.

* POTENTIAL IMPACTS...Steep beaches will have a higher risk of
sneaker wave activity with greater wave run-up onto beaches than
normally expected. Unsuspecting beach-goers may be suddenly
pulled out to sea. Never turn your back to the ocean!
properties.instruction:
A Beach Hazard Statement for sneaker waves means that conditions
are present to support a heightened risk of unsuspecting beach
goers being swept into the sea by a wave. People walking along the
beach should never turn their back to the sea. Fisherman should
avoid fishing from rocks or jetties.

NWSheadline: BEACH HAZARDS STATEMENT IN EFFECT FROM LATE TONIGHT THROUGH TUESDAY EVENING

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued March 18 at 2:27PM PDT expiring March 20 at 11:00PM PDT by NWS Sacramento CA
properties.description:
A Pacific storm will bring snow to the Sierra, impacting travel
over passes. Light to moderate snow amounts are expected, which
could bring travel delays due to slippery, snow covered roads.
Lighter snow shower activity continues into early Thursday with
little additional accumulation.
* WHAT...Snow expected. Plan on difficult travel conditions,
including during the morning and evening commutes on Wednesday.
Total snow accumulations of 6 to 9 inches, with localized
amounts up to 12 inches, are expected.

* WHERE...West Slope Northern Sierra Nevada. Sierra passes
including Donner Pass on Interstate 80, Echo Summit on Highway
50 and Carson Pass on Highway 88. Heaviest snowfall is
expected from Highway 50 southward.

* WHEN...8 PM Tuesday to 11 PM Wednesday.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Be prepared for reduced visibilities at
times.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Weather Advisory for snow means periods of snow will
cause primarily travel difficulties. Be prepared for snow covered
roads and limited visibilities, and use caution while driving.
The latest road conditions for the state you are calling from can
be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY IN EFFECT FROM 8 PM TUESDAY TO 11 PM PDT WEDNESDAY ABOVE 6000 FEET

recede to near 9.0 FT Wednesday morning then forecast to fluctuate
near 9.0 FT thru Wednesday afternoon.

* SURF...10 to 12 feet, mainly on west facing beaches.

currents can pull swimmers and surfers out to sea. Large

dangerous swimming conditions. Swim near a lifeguard. If caught
in a rip current, relax and float. Don't swim against the
current. If able, swim in a direction following the shoreline. If
unable to escape, face the shore and call or wave for help.

Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

Stay away or be swept away. River banks and culverts can become
unstable and unsafe.

Please report flooding to your local law enforcement agency when you
can do so safely.

properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued March 18 at 4:45PM AST expiring March 20 at 6:00AM AST by NWS San Juan PR
properties.description:
* LOCATION...Beaches of north central Puerto Rico.

* TIMING...Through late Tuesday night.

* IMPACTS...Strong currents that can carry out to sea even the
best of swimmers.
properties.instruction:
There is a high risk of rip currents.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

NWSheadline: HIGH RIP CURRENT RISK NOW IN EFFECT THROUGH LATE TUESDAY NIGHT

properties.areaDesc: Mendocino Coast; Coastal Del Norte; Northern Humboldt Coast; Southwestern Humboldt
properties.headline: Beach Hazards Statement issued March 18 at 1:40PM PDT expiring March 19 at 7:00PM PDT by NWS Eureka CA
properties.description:
A building long-period westerly swell will likely result in a
moderate to high sneaker wave threat tonight through Tuesday
evening. Beachgoers should use caution along area beaches and keep
a safe distance from the surf zone, as waves may suddenly wash
much farther up the beach than expected after several minutes of
relatively smaller waves.
* TIMING...The highest sneaker wave risk will be late tonight
through Tuesday evening.

* IMPACTS...Larger surf at offshore breaks and an enhanced risk
of sneaker waves on northwest California beaches. Steep
beaches will have a higher risk of sneaker wave activity with
greater wave run-up onto beaches. Large waves will also wash
over jetties and rock outcroppings that may normally stay dry.
properties.instruction:
A Beach Hazard Statement is issued when threats such as sneaker
waves and other hazards create life-threatening conditions in the
surf zone. Caution should be used when in or near the water.

NWSheadline: BEACH HAZARDS STATEMENT REMAINS IN EFFECT FROM 11 PM PDT THIS EVENING THROUGH TUESDAY EVENING

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued March 18 at 12:35PM AKDT expiring March 18 at 10:00PM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks, AK
properties.description:
* WHAT...Snow and blowing snow with low visibility occuring.
Plan on difficult travel conditions. Total snow accumulations
of 1 to 2 inches are expected.

* WHERE...Central Beaufort Sea Coast.

* WHEN...Until 10 PM today. The worst conditions are now
developing and will continue into this afternoon. Conditions
will begin to improve by evening as winds decrease.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds gusting as high as 40 mph will cause
areas of blowing and drifting snow reducing the visibility to
one half mile or less at times.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Weather Advisory for blowing snow means periods of
blowing snow will cause travel difficulties. The latest road
conditions can be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 10 PM AKDT THIS EVENING

properties.headline: Blizzard Warning issued March 18 at 12:35PM AKDT expiring March 18 at 10:00PM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks, AK
properties.description:
* WHAT...Blizzard conditions and high winds occuring. Travel
will be very difficult to impossible.

* WHERE...Eastern Beaufort Sea Coast.

* WHEN...Until 10 PM today. The strongest winds and worst
conditions are expected this afternoon.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...West winds gusting to 60 mph will cause
whiteout conditions in blowing snow. Significant drifting of
the snow is likely.
properties.instruction:
A Blizzard Warning means severe winter weather conditions are
expected or occurring. Falling and blowing snow with strong winds
and poor visibilities are likely. This will lead to whiteout
conditions, making travel extremely difficult. The latest road
conditions can be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: BLIZZARD WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 10 PM AKDT THIS EVENING

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued March 18 at 12:35PM AKDT expiring March 18 at 4:00PM AKDT by NWS Fairbanks, AK
properties.description:
* WHAT...Snow and blowing snow with low visibility occurring.
Plan on difficult travel conditions. Additional snow
accumulations of up to one inch are expected.

* WHERE...Northeastern Brooks Range including the Dalton Highway.

* WHEN...Until 4 PM today. The worst conditions are now
developing and will continue into this afternoon. Winds will
decrease in this evening and visibility will begin to improve
then.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Winds gusting as high as 35 mph will
cause areas of blowing and drifting snow and reducing the
visibility to one half mile or less at times. This will make
travel on the Dalton Highway difficult from Atigun Pass north.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Weather Advisory for blowing snow means periods of
blowing snow will cause travel difficulties. The latest road
conditions can be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

NWSheadline: WINTER WEATHER ADVISORY REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 4 PM AKDT THIS AFTERNOON

properties.areaDesc: Gulf waters from East Cape Sable to Chokoloskee 20 to 60 NM out and beyond 5 fathoms; Gulf of Mexico including Dry Tortugas and Rebecca Shoal Channel
properties.headline: Small Craft Advisory issued March 18 at 4:31PM EDT expiring March 19 at 5:00AM EDT by NWS Key West FL
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Key West has issued a Small Craft
Advisory for the Gulf waters beyond five fathoms, including the
Dry Tortugas.

* WINDS...Northeast winds will increase to 20 to 25 knots across
the affected coastal waters.

* WAVES/SEAS...Seas will build to 7 feet across the deeper
portions of the Gulf of Mexico, especially northwest of the Dry
Tortugas.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 20 to 33 knots,
or seas of 7 feet or greater, are expected to produce hazardous
conditions for small craft. Inexperienced boaters, especially
those with smaller vessels, should avoid operating in these
conditions.

NWSheadline: SMALL CRAFT ADVISORY IN EFFECT

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 3:09PM CDT expiring March 19 at 3:15PM CDT by NWS Des Moines IA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Des Moines  has issued a

* Flood Warning for...
Snowmelt in...
Southwestern Kossuth County in north central Iowa...

* Until 315 PM CDT Tuesday.

* At 308 PM CDT, emergency management reported flooding in
Whittemore. Water levels of the flooding remained stable, with
water continuing to flow across some roads in town.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include... Whittemore.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Be especially cautious at night when it is harder to recognize the
dangers of flooding.

properties.instruction:
There is a high risk of rip currents.

Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore, which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as groins, jetties
and piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards, beach patrol flags and
signs.

Swim near a lifeguard. If caught in a rip current, relax and
float. Don't swim against the current. If able, swim in a
direction following the shoreline. If unable to escape, face the
shore and call or wave for help.

properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued March 18 at 12:29PM MDT by NWS Riverton WY
properties.description:
The following message is transmitted at the request of the
Air Quality Division of the Wyoming Department of Environmental
Quality.

The Air Quality Division has issued an Ozone Action Day for
Tuesday, March 19, 2019 for the Upper Green River Basin Ozone
Nonattainment Area. An Ozone Action Day is issued when forecasted
weather conditions are favorable for the formation of ozone. Ozone
appears to be elevated in the basin when there is a presence of
ozone-forming precursor emissions including oxides of nitrogen and
volatile organic compounds coupled with meteorological conditions
such as strong temperature inversions, low winds, snow cover, and
sunlight.

During the winter ozone season (January-March), everyone should
take actions to reduce precursor emissions and ground-level ozone
formation.

Ozone is an air pollutant that can cause respiratory distress
especially to children, the elderly, and people with existing
respiratory conditions such as asthma.  People in these sensitive
groups should limit strenuous or extended outdoor activities,
especially in the afternoon and evening.

For more information on ozone and the health effects of ozone,
please visit the websites for the Wyoming Department of
Environmental Quality at deq.wyoming.gov and the Wyoming
Department of Health at www.health.wyo.gov.

Current information on ozone levels at the Air Quality Division's
monitoring stations at Daniel South, Pinedale, Boulder, Big
Piney, and Juel Spring can be found at www.wyvisnet.com.

NWSheadline: Ozone Action Day in Effect for Tuesday, March 19, 2019 for the Upper Green River Basin Ozone Nonattainment Area

* Flood Warning for...
Northwestern Warren County in west central Mississippi...
Northwestern Yazoo County in central Mississippi...
Central Issaquena County in west central Mississippi...
Southeastern Sharkey County in west central Mississippi...

* Until 345 PM CDT Thursday.

* Significant flooding is ongoing in these areas due to rising
backwater from the closure of the Steele Bayou gates and excessive
rainfall runoff from areas upstream. In addition, the Muddy Bayou
Structure has now been closed.

* The gage at Steele Bayou was at 96.6 feet as of noon, March 18. It
is expected to reach 97 to 97.5 feet. The extent of the current
flood waters is expected to increase in area until the gates of
Steele Bayou are opened again. This may come during early-mid
April if no more significant rains fall in the basin.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Valley Park, Holly Bluff, Fitler, Eagle Lake, Onward and Satartia.

* Major thoroughfares such as Highway 61 North and South remain
open, but Highway 465 between Highway 61 and Eagle Lake, Highway
16 between Rolling Fork and Holly Bluff, and several smaller
county roads are closed due to this flooding.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Excessive runoff from heavy rainfall will cause flooding of small
creeks and streams, country roads, farmland, and other low lying
spots.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued March 18 at 12:41PM EDT expiring March 19 at 2:00PM EDT by NWS Grand Rapids MI
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Grand Rapids has extended the

* Flood Advisory for...
Rain and Snowmelt in...
Newaygo County in west central Michigan...

* Until 200 PM EDT Tuesday.

* At 1233 PM EDT, emergency management officials reported ongoing
flooding and road closures caused by the heavy rainfall and
melting snow late last week. No additional heavy rain is expected
this week, but gradual snowmelt will continue. Water levels will
remain high for a few more days on streams and lakes in the area,
but will continue to slowly fall.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Newaygo, White Cloud, Fremont, Hesperia, Grant, Croton, Bridgeton,
Brohman, Woodland Park, Hawkins, Reeman, Woodville, Bitely, Croton
Heights, Wooster and Brunswick.
properties.instruction:
Turn around, don't drown when encountering flooded roads. Most flood
deaths occur in vehicles.

Please report flooding to your local law enforcement agency when you
can do so safely.

Muskegon River At Newaygo affecting Newaygo County
Muskegon River At Bridgeton affecting Newaygo County
Maple River At Maple Rapids affecting Clinton County

.Minor flooding is still ongoing after snowmelt and rain several days
ago. Meanwhile dry conditions will continue through the remainder of
the week which should allow for some gradual improvement in flood
conditions. The following forecast is based on observed and forecast
48 hour precipitation.
The Flood Warning continues for
the Maple River At Maple Rapids.
* until Thursday afternoon.
* at 12:15 PM Monday the stage was 9.2 feet.
* Flood stage is 9.0 feet.
* Minor Flooding is occurring and Minor Flooding is forecast.
* Forecast, the river will continue to fall below flood stage by
Wednesday evening.
* Impact, at 9.0 feet...Expect minor flooding of County Line Road and
a home along County Line Road.
* Flood history, this crest compares to a crest of 9.7 feet on Apr 11
2017. A crest of 10.0 feet occurred on Feb 22 2018.

properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Hastings has extended the

* Flood Warning for...
Southeastern Nance County in central Nebraska...
Central Merrick County in central Nebraska...

* Until 245 PM CDT Tuesday.

* At 1118 AM CDT, automated river gauges continued to report

Central City, Clarks, Silver Creek and Archer.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 11:05AM CDT by NWS Paducah KY
properties.description:
Mississippi River at Cape Girardeau...Thebes and New Madrid

.Moderate flooding continues along the Mississippi River at Cape
Girardeau, Thebes, and New Madrid. At Cape Girardeau and Thebes,
water levels continue to rise, with a crest near 40.5 feet expected
Saturday at both locations. At New Madrid, the river will crest near
41.0 feet Wednesday.
The Flood Warning continues for
the Mississippi River at Cape Girardeau
* until further notice.
* At 10:30 AM Monday the stage was 37.1 feet.
* Flood Stage is 32.0 feet.
* Moderate flooding is occurring and Moderate flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...The river will continue rising to near 40.5 feet by
Saturday evening then begin falling.
* Impact...At 42.0 Feet...Several homes and structures in southern
Cape Girardeau County may be inundated or cut off due to backwater
flooding from the Diversion Channel. Evacuations may be required.
Thousands of acres are flooded. Numerous roads are closed both
along the Mississippi River and due to backwater flooding.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 11:05AM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
Mississippi River At Donaldsonville affecting Ascension Parish

Mississippi River At Reserve affecting St. Charles...St. James and
St. John The Baptist Parishes

...The flood warning continues for the following rivers in
Louisiana...

Mississippi River At Red River Landing affecting East Baton
Rouge...Pointe Coupee and West Feliciana Parishes

Mississippi River At Baton Rouge affecting East Baton Rouge and
West Baton Rouge Parishes
The Flood Warning continues for
The Mississippi River At Red River Landing.
* Until further notice.
* At 10:00 AM Monday the stage was 61.8 feet.
* Moderate flooding is occurring and Moderate flooding is forecast.
* Flood stage is 48.0 feet.
* Forecast...The river will continue to fall to a stage of 61.8 feet
by Tuesday March 19.
* Impact...At 61.6 feet...Flood of March 24, 1997.
* Impact...At 59.0 feet...The east bank levee will be topped and the
prison farm land between the two levees will be inundated. Angola
Landing will be under water closing the ferry there. All river
islands along the reach from Red River Landing to Baton Rouge will
remain inundated with recreational camps and river bottom farm land
under water.
* Impact...At 58.0 feet...Angola farmland on the left bank becomes
inundated.
* Impact...At 54.0 feet...All river islands along the reach from Red
River Landing to Baton Rouge will be inundated. Recreational camps
and river bottom land will be under water. Water approaches Angola
farm land.
* Impact...At 51.0 feet...All river islands along the reach from Red
River Landing to Baton Rouge will be inundated. Recreational camps
and river bottom farm land will be under water.
* Impact...At 48.0 feet...Access roads will be inundated and
evacuation of all river islands must be complete. Protection of
people and property in the river bottom land on the river side of
the levees must be complete.
* Impact...At 46.0 feet...River traffic will become dangerous. A levee
crevasse would flood adjacent farm land. Significant flooding of
Raccourci Island will continue and evacuation of the island is
recommended.
* Impact...At 45.0 feet...Between the 40 and 45 foot stage flooding of
Raccourci Island becomes significant. At the 45 foot stage
evacuation of the island is recommended.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 11:05AM CDT by NWS New Orleans LA
properties.description:
Mississippi River At Donaldsonville affecting Ascension Parish

Mississippi River At Reserve affecting St. Charles...St. James and
St. John The Baptist Parishes

...The flood warning continues for the following rivers in
Louisiana...

Mississippi River At Red River Landing affecting East Baton
Rouge...Pointe Coupee and West Feliciana Parishes

Mississippi River At Baton Rouge affecting East Baton Rouge and

The Flood Warning continues for
The Mississippi River At Baton Rouge.
* Until further notice.
* At 10:00 AM Monday the stage was 43.9 feet.
* Major flooding is occurring and Major flooding is forecast.
* Flood stage is 35.0 feet.
* Forecast...The river will continue rising to near 44.0 feet by
Monday March 18. Additional rises may be possible thereafter.
* Impact...At 43.0 feet...Shipping and industrial activities are
significantly affected. Unprotected low-lying areas will be flooded
and agricultural operations will be impacted on the west side of
the river. The city of Baton Rouge is protected by levees at this
level.
* Impact...At 40.0 feet...The grounds of the older part of Louisiana
State University's campus become soggy. This includes the area
around the Veterinary Medicine building, the Veterinary Medicine
Annex, the stadium and ball fields. The city of Baton Rouge and the
main LSU campus are protected by levees at this level.
* Impact...At 38.0 feet...River traffic and industrial activity on the
river side of the levees will be greatly affected. Navigational
safety regulations will be strictly enforced.
* Impact...At 36.0 feet...River traffic and industrial activity on the
river side of the levees will be greatly affected. Navigational
safety regulations will be strictly enforced.
* Impact...At 35.0 feet...River islands from Red River Landing

properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Omaha has issued a

* Flood Warning for...
Mills County in southwestern Iowa...
Monona County in west central Iowa...
Western Pottawattamie County in southwestern Iowa...
Fremont County in southwestern Iowa...
Harrison County in southwestern Iowa...
Madison County in northeastern Nebraska...
Burt County in east central Nebraska...
Lancaster County in southeastern Nebraska...
Pierce County in northeastern Nebraska...
Saunders County in east central Nebraska...
Wayne County in northeastern Nebraska...
Cuming County in northeastern Nebraska...
Washington County in east central Nebraska...
Dodge County in east central Nebraska...
Otoe County in southeastern Nebraska...
Nemaha County in southeastern Nebraska...
Eastern Jefferson County in southeastern Nebraska...
Seward County in southeastern Nebraska...
Douglas County in east central Nebraska...
Saline County in southeastern Nebraska...
Sarpy County in east central Nebraska...
Thurston County in northeastern Nebraska...
Richardson County in southeastern Nebraska...
Gage County in southeastern Nebraska...
Stanton County in northeastern Nebraska...
Cass County in southeastern Nebraska...

* Until 1100 AM CDT Tuesday.

* At 1054 AM CDT, flooding continues in many areas along and near
streams that are receding. Many county roads still have water on
them due the recent flood event and it will take a while for that
water to drain out. Locations with feeder streams that go into the
Missouri River, the Platte River, the Elkhorn River, the Big Blue
River and the Nishnabotna River are the most likely to see water
problems outside of the larger river flooding. This is an
extension and expansion of a previous areal flood warning.

* Some locations that could experience flooding include...
Omaha, Lincoln, Norfolk, Beatrice, Falls City, Council Bluffs,
Bellevue, Fremont, Papillion, La Vista, Blair, Nebraska City,
Seward, Crete, Plattsmouth, Ralston, Wayne, Glenwood, Gretna and
Auburn.

* Stay out of flooded areas. Turn around, don't drown when
encountering flooded roads. Most flood deaths occur in vehicles.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued March 18 at 10:34AM CDT expiring March 19 at 1:30PM CDT by NWS North Platte NE
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in North Platte has extended the

* Flood Advisory for Minor Flooding in Poor Drainage Areas for...
Rain and Snowmelt in...
Northern Rock County in north central Nebraska...
Northern Brown County in north central Nebraska...
Holt County in north central Nebraska...
Keya Paha County in north central Nebraska...
Boyd County in north central Nebraska...

* Until 130 PM CDT Tuesday.

* At 1031 AM CDT, Nebraska Department of Transportation continues to
report critical disruptions along Nebraska roads including
Nebraska Highway 11 in both directions, Nebraska Highway 12 in
both directions, and US 281 in both directions because of
flooding. Emergency management reported numerous roads continue to
be closed or impassable across portions of central and north
central Nebraska due to flooding. Also, portions of the Elkhorn
River remain above minor flood stage. This includes locations near
Atkinson, O'Neill, and Ewing in Holt County. Additional runoff
today may worsen flooding and cause water to remain on some area
roads or higher river levels on area rivers.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Ainsworth, Bassett, Spencer, Springview, O'Neill, Atkinson,
Stuart, Ewing, Butte, Long Pine, Lynch, Page, Newport, Naper,
Johnstown, Gross, Norden, Inman and Bristow.

Additional liquid precipitation of a quarter of an inch is expected
over the area overnight. This additional rain may result in minor
contributions to the flooding.

This includes the following highways...
Highway 183 between mile markers 173 and 225.
Highway 20 between mile markers 226 and 328.
Highway 281 between mile markers 170 and 223.
Highway 12 between mile markers 24 and 135.
properties.instruction:
Keep children away from storm drains, culverts, creeks and streams.
Water levels can rise rapidly and sweep children away.

Excessive runoff from heavy rainfall will cause flooding of small
creeks and streams, country roads, farmland, and other low lying
spots.

A Flood Advisory means river or stream flows are elevated, or ponding
of water in urban or other areas is occurring or is imminent.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 10:55AM EDT by NWS Gaylord MI
properties.description:
Rifle River near Sterling AFFECTING Arenac County

.The Rifle Rive remains above flood stage due to recent rain and
snowmelt. In addition, with temperatures back to below freezing, ice
jams have likely also formed on the river leading to fluctuating
river levels.

The river is forecast to drop below flood stage late Tuesday night.
However, ice jams and the resulting flooding are very difficult if
not impossible to predict and may last from several hours to several
days. A break-up of an ice jam can quickly produce flooding
downstream of the jam. Persons in the warned area along the river
should remain aware of and be prepared for rapidly changing river
levels and take steps to protect property from rising water.
The Flood Warning continues for
The Rifle River near Sterling.
* until further notice.
* At 10:30 AM Monday the stage was 8.2 feet.

by tomorrow morning.

Airport, and moderate to heavy rain is expected to continue into

NWSheadline: HEAVY RAINS TO CONTINUE TODAY WITH STREAMS AND RIVERS CLOSE TO BANKFULL

properties.areaDesc: Taiya Inlet and Klondike Highway; Eastern Chichagof Island; Cape Decision to Salisbury Sound Coastal Area; Haines Borough and Lynn Canal; Juneau Borough and Northern Admiralty Island; Salisbury Sound to Cape Fairweather Coastal Area; Glacier Bay
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 6:46AM AKDT by NWS Juneau AK
properties.description:
Rainfall on Sunday from an atmospheric river that moved through
the northern panhandle totaled 1 to 4 inches, with the largest
amounts in northern Glacier Bay. The 2.11 inches at the Haines
Airport was enough to break the daily record for preciptiation,
and Skagway's 1.22 inches was also enough to break that daily
record as well.

Streams and rivers in the northern panhandle responded as
expected with all the rain and snowmelt. Water levels in the area
rose between 2 to 4 feet, with the Salmon River near Gustavus
having the biggest rise. Even with all these rises, there was no
flooding on the northern panhandle streams.

NWSheadline: HEAVY RAINFALL INCREASED STREAMS AND RIVER HEIGHTS IN THE NORTHERN PANHANDLE

properties.headline: High Surf Warning issued March 18 at 4:32AM HST expiring March 18 at 6:00PM HST by NWS Honolulu HI
properties.description:
..HIGH SURF ADVISORY FOR THE WEST FACING SHORES OF THE BIG
ISLAND...

.The large north-northwest swell has peaked and begun to slowly
lower early this morning. Warning-level surf will continue today,
then lower to advisory levels by Tuesday along exposed north and
west facing shores.
* SURF...25 to 40 feet this morning, lowering to 18 to 24 feet
tonight along north and west facing shores of Niihau and Kauai,
and along north facing shores of Oahu, Molokai, and Maui. 15 to
25 feet this morning, lowering to 8 to 12 feet tonight along
exposed north facing shores of the Big Island. 15 to 25 feet
this morning, lowering to 12 to 18 feet tonight along west
facing shores of Oahu and Molokai.

* TIMING...through this afternoon.

* IMPACTS...Very High...Expect ocean water surging and sweeping
across beaches, coastal benches, and lava flows creating the
potential for impacts to coastal properties and infrastructure,
including roadways. Powerful longshore and rip currents will be
present at most beaches.
properties.instruction:
These dangerous conditions mean that only highly experienced
persons should enter the water. Inexperienced persons should
remain off beaches and adjacent beachfront areas. Large breaking
surf, significant shorebreak, and dangerous currents make
entering the water very hazardous.

NWSheadline: HIGH SURF WARNING REMAINS IN EFFECT UNTIL 6 PM HST THIS EVENING

properties.headline: Marine Weather Statement issued March 18 at 3:51AM HST by NWS Honolulu HI
properties.description:
A significant late season north northwest swell currently
impacting the islands will be capable of producing surges in the
exposed harbors today. Currents within the harbors could become
strong enough to damage boats due to jostling of docks. This swell
will also result in large breaking waves near harbor entrances.
Mariners should exercise extra caution today when entering or
leaving port, and when mooring or launching vessels.

Tennessee River At Clifton affecting Decatur...Hardin...Perry and Wayne
Counties

. The Tennessee River at Clifton has fallen below flood stage but will remain
above action stage through most of the week. The river will continue to fall
as no significant rainfall is forecast to fall this week.
The National Weather Service in Nashville, Tn has issued a
* Flood Advisory for
The Tennessee River At Clifton
* At 8 AM the river was estimated to be at 370.0 feet and falling.
* Flood stage is 370.0 feet.
* The river will continue to fall to near 368.9 feet by tomorrow morning.
* At 370.0 feet...In Decatur County, the boat launch and parking lot areas of
Riverstone Marina are flooded. In Wayne County, water begins to flood portions
of Beechview Drive and the Beech Lake Campground on Beech Lake Road. In Perry
County, access roads in the Peters Landing area including Peters Landing Road
begin to flood. In Hardin County, in the Cobb Farm area of Nance Bend and low
lying portions of Senator Cobb Road and Colonel James Hardin Drive begin to
flood and access may be limited.
* At 369.0 feet...In Decatur County, water inundates Scenic Lane in the Russ
Farm area, cutting off all access to riverfront homes in the area.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Stay tuned to noaa weather radio or other local media for further information
from the National Weather Service.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 8:11AM CDT expiring March 20 at 12:00AM CDT by NWS Kansas City/Pleasant HIll MO
properties.description:
Platte River At Sharps Station affecting Platte County.

Platte River near Platte City affecting Platte County.
The Flood Warning continues for
The Platte River near Platte City.
* until late Tuesday night.
* At  1:21 PM Sunday the stage was 26.5 feet.
* Flood stage is 20.0 feet.
* Moderate flooding is occurring and Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...The river will continue to fall to below flood stage by
early Tuesday morning.
* At 25.0 feet...Water overtops 1st Street in Tracy, Missouri.
* At 22.0 feet...Flooding occurs at Humphreys Access Area which is
located 5 miles downstream from Platte City. 300 acres of pasture
are also flooded.
* At 20.0 feet...Cropland near State Highway 92 near Platte City
begins to flood.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Do not drive through flowing water. Nearly half of all flood
fatalities are vehicle related. As little as 6 inches of water may
cause you to lose control of your vehicle. Two feet of water will
carry most vehicles away.This product along with additional weather
and stream information is available at www.weather.gov/kc/.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued March 18 at 8:44AM EDT expiring March 21 at 2:00AM EDT by NWS Newport/Morehead City NC
properties.description:
Neuse River At Kinston affecting Lenoir County
The Flood Warning continues for
The Neuse River At Kinston.
* until late Wednesday night.
* At  8 AM Monday the stage was 14.5 feet.
* Minor flooding is occurring and Minor flooding is forecast.
* Flood stage is 14.0 feet.
* Forecast...The river will continue to fall to below flood stage by
Wednesday evening.
* Impact...At 14.0 feet...Water overflows into lowlands adjacent to
the river. Water access docks are also affected.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Do not drive vehicles through flooded areas. Most flood deaths occur
in automobiles when people try to drive through flooded areas.

Stay tuned to developments by listening to NOAA Weather Radio...local
radio...media or cable TV.

properties.areaDesc: Coastal Kenedy; Coastal Willacy; Coastal Cameron
properties.headline: Coastal Flood Statement issued March 18 at 4:21AM CDT expiring March 18 at 7:00PM CDT by NWS Brownsville TX
properties.description:
Northeast winds have diminished, but fetch across the Gulf of
Mexico will produce elevated seas along the Lower Texas Coast.
This will maintain the likelihood of minor coastal flooding at
local beaches with the peak being around high tide.
* COASTAL FLOODING...Breaking waves will continue to run up on the
beaches until at least around sunset today.

* Timing...Beach inundation will increase after noon today,
peaking around high tide at 405 PM CDT.

* IMPACTS...Dangerous beach driving and poor walking conditions.
Generally, a foot or less of water may flood beach chairs,
umbrellas, tents, and trash cans at their usual locations.
properties.instruction:
Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore...which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as groins...
jetties and piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards and beach patrol
flags and signs.

If you become caught in a strong current...yell for help. Remain
calm. Do not exhaust yourself and stay afloat while waiting for
help. If you have to swim out of a strong current, swim parallel
to shore and back toward the beach when possible. Do not attempt
to swim directly against strong currents as you will tire
quickly.

NWSheadline: HIGH RIP CURRENT RISK IS CANCELLED... ...COASTAL FLOOD STATEMENT UNTIL 7 PM CDT THIS EVENING

properties.areaDesc: Elbert; Stephens; Hart; Franklin; Habersham; Rabun
properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued March 18 at 4:25AM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
Relative humidity values will fall to around 20 percent this
afternoon. Northwest winds of 10 to 15 mph with gusts to 20 mph
are expected as well. This combined with low fuel moisture values
will result in enhanced fire danger this afternoon.

Please refer to your local burn permitting authorities on whether
you can burn today. If you do burn, use extreme caution since
fires can quickly get out of hand under these conditions.

NWSheadline: FIRE DANGER STATEMENT IN EFFECT FROM 2 PM EDT THIS AFTERNOON THROUGH THIS EVENING

properties.headline: Air Quality Alert issued March 17 at 1:36PM MDT by NWS Riverton WY
properties.description:
The following message is transmitted at the request of the
Air Quality Division of the Wyoming Department of Environmental
Quality.

The Air Quality Division has issued an Ozone Action Day for
Monday, March 18, 2019 for the Upper Green River Basin Ozone
Nonattainment Area. An Ozone Action Day is issued when forecasted
weather conditions are favorable for the formation of ozone. Ozone
appears to be elevated in the basin when there is a presence of
ozone-forming precursor emissions including oxides of nitrogen and
volatile organic compounds coupled with meteorological conditions
such as strong temperature inversions, low winds, snow cover, and
sunlight.

During the winter ozone season (January-March), everyone should
take actions to reduce precursor emissions and ground-level ozone
formation.

Ozone is an air pollutant that can cause respiratory distress
especially to children, the elderly, and people with existing
respiratory conditions such as asthma.  People in these sensitive
groups should limit strenuous or extended outdoor activities,
especially in the afternoon and evening.

For more information on ozone and the health effects of ozone,
please visit the websites for the Wyoming Department of
Environmental Quality at deq.wyoming.gov and the Wyoming
Department of Health at www.health.wyo.gov.

Current information on ozone levels at the Air Quality Division's
monitoring stations at Daniel South, Pinedale, Boulder, Big
Piney, and Juel Spring can be found at www.wyvisnet.com.

NWSheadline: Ozone Action Day in Effect for Monday, March 18, 2019 for the Upper Green River Basin Ozone Nonattainment Area
